						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Option 5: a bad idea, possibly damaging the regulators.  They're both trying to regulate the output voltage on the rail.  They are most likely not both IDENTICAL throughout the entire operating range.  What happens is they will both be 'argueing' about what the exact voltage should be which results in high and possibly damaging currents.</div><s>Specifically in the case of the 7805, it would be &quot;ok&quot;: they wouldn&#39;t fight. 7805s can only source current, so when they disagreed, one would end up sourcing the vast majority or all of the current.</s><br /><br />edit: Ok, I took a Fairchild MC7805C and hooked OUT and GND to a bench supply. Unfortunately, my ammeter has a blown fuse so I only have the gauges on the bench supply, but it showed:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Vout Iin<br />50dV 0cA<br />51dV 1cA<br />52dV 2cA<br />57dV 3cA</div> Units have specifically been chosen (decivolts, centiamps) to show how stupidly little precision I have. So I'm wrong, but looking at the equivalent circuit for a 7805, I'm not certain what's doing the sinking.</div>

					
